<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Written evidence submitted by the Equality Challenge Unit (WSC051)</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><h1 style="margin:0pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-before:always; page-break-inside:avoid; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence submitted by the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Equality Challenge Unit (WSC051)</span></h1><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Introduction</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">This evidence is submitted on </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">a corporate basis by Equality Challenge Unit</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> (ECU)</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">ECU i</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">s a charity which works to further and support equality and diversity for staff and students in higher education across all four nations of the UK, and in colleges in Scotland. ECU receives its core </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">funding from </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Universities UK, GuildHE, the Higher Education Funding Council for England, the Higher Education Funding Council for Wales, the Scottish Funding Council and the Department for Employment and Learning in Northern Ireland.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Athena SWAN Charter</span></p><p style="margin:12pt 0pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">One of ECU’s core activities is the Athena SWAN Charter. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Founded in 2005, the Athena SWAN Charter is a scheme that recognises excellence in science, engineering</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">technology</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">, mathematics and medicine (STEMM</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">) employment</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> for women in higher education.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">The </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Charter receives addition</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">al</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> funding from the Royal Society, the Biochemical Society, the Department of Health and the Scottish Funding Council.</span></p><p style="margin:12pt 0pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Any university or research institute embedded within a university that is committed to the advancement of the ca</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">reers of women </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">in STEMM </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">can become a member of the Charter, accepting and promoting the six Charter principles:</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:12pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Addressing gender inequalities requires commitment and action from everyone, at all levels of the organisation</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">A change in cultures and attitude</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">s across the organisation is required to tackle the unequal representation of women in science</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">The absence of diversity at management and policy-making levels has broad implications which the organisation will examine</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">The high loss rate of women in science</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> is an urgent concern which the organisation will address</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">The system of short term contracts has particularly negative consequences for the retention and progression of women in science, which the university recognises</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">There are both personal and structura</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">l obstacles to women making the transition from PhD into a sustainable academic career in science, which require the active consideration of the organisation</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:12pt 0pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">There are currently </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">91</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> members of the Charter. Once Charter signatories, universities and their S</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">TEMM </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">departments are encouraged to submit for Athena SWAN Charter recognition awards at Bronze, Silver or Gold level.</span></p><p style="margin:12pt 0pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">The Charter recognises the commitment of universities and university departments to reduce the</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">decline in the numbers </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">of women in </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">S</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">TEMM</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> ac</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">ademic careers </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">further up the career ladder, and </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">retain women graduates and PhD students in academic careers</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:12pt 0pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">This response is based on ECU’s work, in particular the experience of working with universities on Athena SWAN.</span></p><ol type="i" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold; margin:5pt 0pt 0pt 10.81pt; padding-left:13pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Why do numbers of women in STEM </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">academic careers decline further up the career ladder?</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">A</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">n individual’s p</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">rogression through </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">an academic career</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> traditionally relies on crossing barriers </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">at key career transition points</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">. Pro</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">motions</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">policies and practices </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">particularly </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">impact on</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">women</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">This </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">is one of the four key areas</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> in which</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> universities and depart</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">ments must demonstrate activity </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">in order to be considered for an Athena SWAN award. The other areas are</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> providing</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">more general </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">career development</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> support</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">examining and changing </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">organisation and </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">culture, and</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> policies around</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> flexibility and managing career breaks</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">The mechanisms for promotion, how opportunities are advertised and applications sought are particularly important areas, particularly as the high usage of short-term contracts in higher education necessitates a continual cycle of going through these mechanisms.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Problems can arise from a number of issues, including senior male-dominated, opaque decision-making systems, and promotion processes that rely on individuals putting themselves forward, or being approached on an individual basis. Implicit biases against women</span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> and gender differences in how individuals assess their competence and put themselves forward for promotion</span><a name="_ftnref3"></a><a href="#_ftn3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> worsen the effects. Furthermore, women are still usually expected to take responsibility for the majority of childcare and this can severely affects careers at an individual level. The expectation that academics be mobile – combined with this expectation – also leads to another significant issue: the two-body problem (where if one member of an academic couple accepts a job in a distant location, it can be very difficult for the other to follow, without their career being negatively affected)</span><a name="_ftnref4"></a><a href="#_ftn4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">. This is increasing in its significance as women become better represented at early career stages</span><a name="_ftnref5"></a><a href="#_ftn5">[5]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Maternity leave remains the main reason for a career break, and our experience shows that many universities enforce women in dual-career families to take responsibility for childcare by restricting paternity leave. Academic research can also be a difficult career for women to phase a return back into, as their research funding cannot always be paused for the period of their leave, and policies and cultures are often underdeveloped in the context of providing a supportive environment for individuals who are under great pressure to resume their research immediately. This means that the current culture of academic science is disproportionately harmful to women.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Gender divides are also reinforced by other common university cultures, such as the implicit expectation that academics work long hours, undervaluing non-research activities, and the frequent requirement in STEMM for individuals to be in a specific lab or the field at set times resulting in lack of opportunities for genuine flexible working. Applications to the Athena SWAN Charter are increasingly indicating that universities operate core hours in which, for example, all meetings should be scheduled. However these are often not fully enforced or overly flexible, for example 9:00-17:30. This means that staff can be excluded from meetings held later in the day, for example if they need to collect children from school. Data on the higher education sector shows that more academic women work part time as compared to men</span><a name="_ftnref6"></a><a href="#_ftn6">[6]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> and our experience indicates that women are more likely to take advantage of more appropriate core hours (e.g. 10:00 – 16:00). This enables women (and men) to continue their careers and fulfil caring responsibilities. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="i" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.86pt; padding-left:13pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">What should universities and the higher education sector do to retain women graduates and PhD students in academic careers? Are there examples of good practice?</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">First and foremost, cultures and attitudes throughout institutions need to change. Change requires strong commitment; more than many realise as the relatively low success rate for first-time Athena SWAN applications shows</span><a name="_ftnref7"></a><a href="#_ftn7">[7]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> Some solutions, such as those highlighted below, can be applied in general terms across the board. However, they must be considered in the context of the culture, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">policies and practices</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> within individual universities, departments and subject areas. Therefore, awareness and self-analysis are vital, as biased and/or discriminatory practices are often not obviously visible.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Targeted solutions have the greatest benefit – identifying key attrition points, harmful cultures and barriers to progression at a local level before is the first step to constructing appropriate solutions. For example, broadly speaking, biological sciences (62%, 2011) have a high percentage of women at undergraduate level as compared to engineering and technology (16%, 2011)</span><a name="_ftnref8"></a><a href="#_ftn8">[8]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">. There will also be variations between the subdivisions of these subjects. Therefore to address disparities between men and women in these two disciplines will require different approaches and solutions. To address retention in these two disciplines will require attention at different transition points, although we recognise that whilst the proportions of women at undergraduate and PhD level vary, men consistently dominate the more senior positions. For example, 85% of full time professors in STEMM are men (2011)</span><a name="_ftnref9"></a><a href="#_ftn9">[9]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 5pt 31.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Athena SWAN does not have a check-list of objective essential activities that universities must do to retain women academics, but activities in the following areas are often highlighted:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="color:#0093d0; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">=</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Appraisals – e.g. regular appraisals carried out and career development discussed</span></p><p style="margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="color:#0093d0; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">=</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Diversity and unconscious bias training – e.g. training provided for all staff involved in recruitment and promotion decisions</span></p><p style="margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="color:#0093d0; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">=</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Transparency of procedures and processes – e.g. individuals selected for posts or given more senior responsibilities through a fair and clear process</span></p><p style="margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="color:#0093d0; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">=</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Committee structures and balance of representation – e.g. women at least proportionally represented and not restricted to the least influential committees</span></p><p style="margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="color:#0093d0; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">=</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Departmental openness and inclusivity – e.g. all staff invited to a weekly coffee morning, at which senior staff are accessible</span></p><p style="margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="color:#0093d0; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">=</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Departmental roles and responsibilities – e.g. less desirable tasks assigned fairly and transparently </span></p><p style="margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="color:#0093d0; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">=</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Visibility of women – e.g. care taken to ensure that the images around the university are not male-dominated, and a good balance amongst invited speakers</span></p><p style="margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="color:#0093d0; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">=</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Valuing staff contribution – e.g. achievements of men and women equally valued, and </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">teaching, research and pastoral </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">activities all </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">recognised </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">and rewarded</span></p><p style="margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="color:#0093d0; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">=</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Workload allocation – e.g. all staff workloads modelled and analysed transparently to make sure individuals are not overburdened, such as with administration</span></p><p style="margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="color:#0093d0; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">=</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Induction and training – e.g. all staff given a comprehensive induction and may be assigned a mentor, with the opportunity to express a preference about that person’s identity.</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 31.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Athena SWAN fact sheets highlight short-term ‘quick wins’ that universities can achieve with regards to organisational culture</span><a name="_ftnref10"></a><a href="#_ftn10">[10]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">, maternity leave/return and flexible working</span><a name="_ftnref11"></a><a href="#_ftn11">[11]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">, and best practices for supporting researchers, especially at early career stages</span><a name="_ftnref12"></a><a href="#_ftn12">[12]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">, which are particularly important</span><a name="_ftnref13"></a><a href="#_ftn13">[13]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><a name="_ftnref14"></a><a href="#_ftn14">[14]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">. These include addressing/making changes in the following areas:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="color:#0093d0; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">=</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Data collection (so the university/department knows what it must act on and can prioritise)</span></p><p style="margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="color:#0093d0; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">=</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Induction, networking and mentoring (see the ECU report Mentoring: progressing women's careers in higher education</span><a name="_ftnref15"></a><a href="#_ftn15">[15]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">)</span></p><p style="margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="color:#0093d0; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">=</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Skills development</span></p><p style="margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="color:#0093d0; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">=</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Appraisal and performance management</span></p><p style="margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="color:#0093d0; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">=</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Inclusion and communication (e.g. consulting staff systematically and utilising or setting up an early career researcher forum)</span></p><p style="margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="color:#0093d0; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">=</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Parental leave.</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; margin:5pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Our 2011 Impact Report</span><a name="_ftnref16"></a><a href="#_ftn16">[16]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> showed engagement in the Athena SWAN to be a key driver for improvement in the above areas, particularly acting as a catalyst for change and something that, crucially, highlights issues that those in influential and decision-making positions may not previously have been aware of. The Charter now has 92 members across the UK and we are seeing an institution-led desire to involve themselves in the process. For example, one of the Liverpool School of Tropical Medicine’s first acts as an independent HEI was to join the Charter</span><a name="_ftnref17"></a><a href="#_ftn17">[17]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Key benefits of engaging with the Charter include: increased representation of women; processes being formalised and more effectively focused; genuine cultural change; and greater encouragement and progression (and therefore retention) at an individual level. Other benefits that help with the sustainability of these changes include: increases in the visibility of senior women; providing a focal point for previously disparate activities; improved processes; better data and understanding of staff; better communications (including regarding support and processes universities already had in place, but were not visible); and the competitive element of the Charter.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="12" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">To better understand the impact and effectiveness of the Charter, we have commissioned the University of Loughborough to do further evaluation of the Athena SWAN Charter to date. The results of this evaluation will available by the end of 2013 and will help us to continue to improve the robustness of the Charter.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="13" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Further good practice is highlighted by the Institute of Physics’ Project Juno (a scheme complementary to the Athena SWAN Charter</span><a name="_ftnref18"></a><a href="#_ftn18">[18]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">) guidance</span><a name="_ftnref19"></a><a href="#_ftn19">[19]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">, the Royal Society of Chemistry’s Planning for Success: Good Practice in University Science Departments publication</span><a name="_ftnref20"></a><a href="#_ftn20">[20]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">, the London Mathematical Society’s Advancing Women In Mathematics: Good Practice in UK University Departments publication</span><a name="_ftnref21"></a><a href="#_ftn21">[21]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> and the ECU Gender portal</span><a name="_ftnref22"></a><a href="#_ftn22">[22]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="i" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 16.92pt; padding-left:13pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">What role should the Government have in encouraging the retention of women in academic STEM careers? </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="14" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Rather than develop new schemes, we believe that the Government should support existing schemes like Athena SWAN, which address retention of women in academic STEMM careers. Supporting existing schemes though funding will allow for schemes to be sustainable and make a difference in the short and medium terms, and in the long term, tackle the root causes of attrition by not focussing on ‘fixing the women’ but on addressing entrenched cultures and biases. More resources for such schemes would make a clear difference to their ability to share good practice and make the case for diversity, which is an area into which the Royal Society is currently carrying out research</span><a name="_ftnref23"></a><a href="#_ftn23">[23]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">. This would enable more support to be provided to universities to approach equality issues in more a sustainable and broad manner.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="15" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 5pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">The rapid interest in and growth of the Athena SWAN Charter is demonstrated by increased numbers of applications (31 in April 2012</span><a name="_ftnref24"></a><a href="#_ftn24">[24]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">  compared with 112 in April 2013) and traction with, for example:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="color:#0093d0; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">=</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">the Department of Health (who contributed £199,700 to Charter development in 2012, after deciding to link funding for NIHR Biomedical Research Centres and Biomedical Research Units to a requirement that the academic partner has achieves a Silver Athena SWAN award)</span><a name="_ftnref25"></a><a href="#_ftn25">[25]</a></p><p style="margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="color:#0093d0; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">=</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Research Councils UK (who recommend participation in schemes such as Athena SWAN)</span><a name="_ftnref26"></a><a href="#_ftn26">[26]</a></p><p style="margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="color:#0093d0; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">=</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">The Royal Society of Edinburgh (whose Tapping all our Talents report recommends that the Scottish Government should expect university STEMM departments to achieve the minimum standards for an Athena SWAN Silver award or equivalent, amongst other recommendations that are applicable across the UK)</span><a name="_ftnref27"></a><a href="#_ftn27">[27]</a></p><p style="margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="color:#0093d0; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">=</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">the London Mathematical Society (who’s recently launched </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Good Practise Scheme dovetails with the Charter)</span><a name="_ftnref28"></a><a href="#_ftn28">[28]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">This groundswell of support indicates that now is a very apposite time to capitalise on this.</span></p><ol start="16" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; margin:5pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">The Government could also consider setting aside specific funding to support individuals who wish to return to a STEMM career following a break. This does not need to be limited to women, although they would be the most benefitted. A successful scheme is already run by the Daphne Jackson Trust, which achieves significant impact with limited resources</span><a name="_ftnref29"></a><a href="#_ftn29">[29]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">. The Government could consider supporting this existing scheme.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="17" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Whatever the Government decides to do, it is important that is works closely with research councils and other research funders as their investment has considerable impact and influence on research careers in higher education.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="18" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">There is current much attention being focussed on the gender elements of STEMM careers in other countries. In Europe for example, gender is cross-cutting theme in all Horizon 2020 programmes</span><a name="_ftnref30"></a><a href="#_ftn30">[30]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">. In northern Europe, government investment and attention has had an impact on the retention and progression of women in STEMM</span><a name="_ftnref31"></a><a href="#_ftn31">[31]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> We suggest that to have the greatest impact, the Government should consider developing ideas and learning from international partners.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">September 2013</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> Athena SWAN Gold department award application form, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">http://www.athenaswan.org.uk/sites/default/files/Athena-SWAN-gold-dept-award.docx</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn2"></a><a href="#_ftnref2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">Moss-Racusin</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">, C, A. et al, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">2012</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font